<note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">The poet appears to make a deliberate distinction
        between the participial noun in line 3 (vēṭṭō­ḷ) and the finite form in line 6 (vēṭṭēm-ē).
        The perfective participial noun (vēṭṭōḷ) suggests a mother who 'one who has the habit of
        wanting' (i.e. she has wanted in the past and will continue to do so). Vēṭṭēm (not vēṭṭōm,
        which would have been possible) is as an ambiguous form (either participial noun or finite
        verb). EW takes it as a finite here, and as a perfective in the sense of an aorist: "we
        started to wish" for something else, i.e. the event with the hero has changed "our" views
        from the ones normal in the community as represented by the mother. On the otherhand, the
        difference could simply be due to dialectical variations of finite forms. </note></entry></standOff>

